<TD ALIGN=center><H1>A Search Interface for my Questions</H1>
 <A HREF=http://mark.overmeer.net>Mark A.C.J. Overmeer</A><BR>
 <A HREF=http://www.ATComputing.nl>AT Computing bv</A><BR>
 Nijmegen, The Netherlands<BR>
 <TT><A HREF=mailto:Mark@Overmeer.net>Mark@Overmeer.net</A></TT>
 <P>&nbsp;</TD></TR>
<TR><TD VALIGN=bottom>
  <A HREF=#abstract>Abstract</A><BR>
  <A HREF=#index>Index</A><BR>
  <A HREF=#related>Related&nbsp;work</A><BR>
  <A HREF=#author>About&nbsp;the&nbsp;author</A><BR>
  </TD><TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100% BGCOLOR=#dddddd>
&nbsp;<P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Current interfaces to Search Engines are based on speed of delivery by
the engine, and ease of use by everyone.  However, if you are really looking
for information, the results are often poor.  In this paper, an experimental
interface is demonstrated which has more ways to control the search and a very
abstract representation of results.  It demands more of the human and the
machine, but should deliver better answers.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</TD></TR>
